findings.title: Privilege Escalation: Self-Elevation to Admin
findings.description: User successfully set their own isAdmin flag to true
findings.remediation: Prevent modification of privilege fields in Firestore rules OR use Custom Claims

findings.title: Privilege Escalation: Self-Elevation to Owner
findings.description: User successfully set their own isOwner flag to true
findings.remediation: Prevent modification of privilege fields in Firestore rules

findings.title: Template injection (Angular/Vue)
findings.description: Template expression "<%= 7*7 %>" was evaluated to "49". This indicates server or client-side template injection.

findings.title: Template injection (Angular sandbox escape)
findings.description: Template expression "{{constructor.constructor("return 7*7")()}}" was evaluated to "49". This indicates server or client-side template injection.

findings.title: User Enumeration via Collection Listing
findings.description: Unauthenticated users can list/enumerate user documents, exposing user data.
findings.remediation: Prevent listing: require authentication and consider restricting list queries

findings.title: Unrestricted Read Access
findings.description: Rule allows anyone to read data without authentication
findings.remediation: Change to: allow read: if request.auth != null
findings._fingerprintSource: cwe:CWE-284||cat:A01||loc:rule:allow read: if true||vuln:rule:allow read: if true||title:unrestricted read access

findings.title: Unauthenticated Read Access to User Data
findings.description: Firestore rules allow unauthenticated users to read user documents. This exposes potentially sensitive user information to anyone.
findings.remediation: Add authentication check: allow read: if request.auth != null

findings.title: Improper Access Control: Unauthenticated User Data Access
findings.description: 3 user profiles readable without authentication
findings.remediation: Change to: allow read: if request.auth != null
findings._fingerprintSource: cwe:CWE-284||cat:A01||title:improper access control: unauthenticated user data access

findings.title: IDOR Vulnerability on User Profiles
findings.description: Users can access other users' profiles by simply changing the document ID in the request.

evidence.detail: alice123 accessed bob456's profile by changing document ID

findings.remediation: Restrict reads to own profile: allow read: if request.auth.uid == userId

findings.title: Retrieved from Cache
findings.description: The content was retrieved from a shared cache. If the response data is sensitive, personal or user-specific, this may result in sensitive information being leaked. In some cases, this may even result in a user gaining complete control of the session of another user, depending on the configuration of the caching components in use in their environment. This is primarily an issue where caching servers such as "proxy" caches are configured on the local network. This configuration is typically found in corporate or educational environments, for instance.

findings.title: X-Content-Type-Options Header Missing
findings.description: The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.

findings.title: Content Security Policy (CSP) Header Not Set
findings.description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page  covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

findings.title: Content Security Policy (CSP) Header Not Set
findings.description: Content Security Policy (CSP) is an added layer of security that helps to detect and mitigate certain types of attacks, including Cross Site Scripting (XSS) and data injection attacks. These attacks are used for everything from data theft to site defacement or distribution of malware. CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page  covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

CSP provides a set of standard HTTP headers that allow website owners to declare approved sources of content that browsers should be allowed to load on that page  covered types are JavaScript, CSS, HTML frames, fonts, images and embeddable objects such as Java applets, ActiveX, audio and video files.

findings.title: X-Content-Type-Options Header Missing
findings.description: The Anti-MIME-Sniffing header X-Content-Type-Options was not set to 'nosniff'. This allows older versions of Internet Explorer and Chrome to perform MIME-sniffing on the response body, potentially causing the response body to be interpreted and displayed as a content type other than the declared content type. Current (early 2014) and legacy versions of Firefox will use the declared content type (if one is set), rather than performing MIME-sniffing.
